  <bioghist id="a8cb31a8f53bfcd6ed576fd459aae747">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Steven Lawry is a social scientist whose career has focused on natural resources, forest management, and land rights. For a period spanning more than ten years, he worked at the Ford Foundation. He started at the Foundation as an Assistant Representative and Program Officer in the Africa and Middle East, South Africa and Namibia Program where he was based in Windhoek, Namibia. Then he moved to the Africa and Middle East, Middle East and North Africa Program where he served as the Foundation's Representative in Cairo, Egypt. He was later appointed Director of the Office of Management Services. While in that position, he briefly served as Acting Representative for the India, Nepal, and Sri Lanka Program.</p><p>After he left the Ford Foundation, Lawry served for a couple of years as the President of Antioch College from 2006 to 2007. He then became a Senior Research Fellow at the Harvard Kennedy School. In 2014, he joined the Center for International Forestry Research (CIFOR) as a Principal Scientist and became a Senior Associate in 2019.</p><p>Lawry earned a B.A. in government and international relations from Florida State University in 1973, a master's degree in urban and regional planning from Florida State University in 1975, and a Ph.D. in land resources from the Nelson Institute for Environmental Studies at the University of Wisconsin-Madison in 1988.</p>  </bioghist>
